
    - creating our own directive based on application requirement called as
      Custom Directive.

    - in angularjs we can use custom directives in 4 ways.

        1. Element
        2. Attribute
        3. CSS Class
        4. Comment

    Ex.
        my_dir

    <my_dir></my_dir>            //Element

    <div my_dir></div>           //Attribute

    <div class="my_dir"></div>   //CSS Class

    <!-- my_dir -->              //Comment


properties of custom directives.
--------------------------------

1. restrict
    this property describes the usage of custom directive.

Ex.
    restrict:"E"   //Element
    restrict:"A"   // Attribute
    restrict:"C"   //CSS Class
    restrict:"M"   //Comment
    restrict:"AE"  //Attribute & Element

[Note : the default value of restrict property is "E"]


2. template
    - this property used to add the inline html to the Custom Directive.

Ex.
    template:"<h1>Welcome to Custom Directives !</h1>"


3. templateUrl
    - this property used to link the external template to the custom directive.

Ex.
    templateUrl : "sample.html"


4. controller
    - this property used to define the controller to the external template of a
      custom directive.

Ex.
    templateUrl:"sample.html",
    controller : "sample"


5. scope
    - this property used to establish the relation between custom directive to
      custom controller.



6. link
    - this property used to manipulate the CSS Present in external template of
      a custom directive.

Syntax of Custom Directive:
---------------------------
app.directive("my_dir",my_dir);
function my_dir(){
    return{
         //Properties of Custom Directives
    }
}
